history.content:
Since we can Phase I 13.5 units now, you should probably Phase I it.

The increased unit cap might actually make it harder to Phase I classes, since those with earlier slots will be able to select more classes. 

____

I beg to differ, you can Phase 2 it, this semester I added after adjustment period and there was still space.

Since we can Phase I 13.5 units now, you should probably Phase I it.

The increased unit cap might actually make it harder to Phase I classes, since those with earlier slots will be able to select more classes.

children.subject: I agree, all that's happened is the gap between people with earlier Phase 1 appointments and later appointments just grew larger (part of why it would be nice to implement a scheme that compensates people with bad Phase 1 appointments by giving them better Phase 2 appointments, and vice verse with respect to people with good Phase 1 appointments)>

Hm, that logic applies even more so to Phase II-ing courses though. More generally, people with high enrollment priorities are benefited more, while people who want to take courses that they don't meet the Phase 1 restrictions for (e.g. undeclared students taking upper-division courses, students taking courses outside their major) are disadvantaged.

This policy change just seems weird in general. The Phase II change made sense since it became a hard cap and didn't affect things much, but I can't reason out what prompted this change.
